<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!--
  DAY-119 — Entitlements for the ad-hoc-signed Dayseam release
  bundle.

  Why this file exists
  ====================

  v0.6.1 shipped completely unsigned. On macOS 13+ an unsigned app
  that calls `NSOpenPanel` (the native folder picker behind Tauri's
  `dialog.open`) gets a *scoped* grant that is not persisted across
  launches. Worse, every child directory the bundle reads inside a
  TCC-protected root (`~/Desktop`, `~/Documents`, `~/Downloads`,
  `~/Public`) can trigger a *separate* consent prompt, which is the
  "5 or 6 pop-ups" cascade users reported when picking a scan root
  for the local-git connector. The connector's protected-name skip
  list (see `crates/connectors/connector-local-git/src/discovery.rs`)
  covers part of that, but without an entitlements grant the OS still
  re-asks on every fresh launch.

  Adding `com.apple.security.files.user-selected.read-write` tells
  TCC that when the user picks a folder via the system picker, the
  resulting grant should persist for the life of the bundle. For a
  hardened-runtime + ad-hoc-signed binary this is the widest the
  grant can be without a Developer ID identity — which we do not
  have yet (see the "Phase 3.5 codesign" tracking issue referenced
  in `.github/workflows/release.yml`).

  Known limitation / follow-up
  ----------------------------

  Ad-hoc signing uses a cdhash-based Designated Requirement, so a
  later release (v0.6.3+) will have a different cdhash from v0.6.2
  and the Keychain may re-prompt once at upgrade time. A truly
  stable DR tied to a bundle id + Team ID requires a Developer ID
  signing identity and is tracked as follow-up work. For v0.6.2
  this is a substantial improvement over v0.6.1 (which shipped
  completely unsigned and therefore re-prompted on every single
  launch, not just on upgrades).

  Why no `app-sandbox`
  ===================

  Sandbox entitlements are intentionally *not* set. The Dayseam
  desktop shell needs to walk user-selected code trees, launch the
  system keyring (macOS Keychain), and open URLs via the `opener`
  crate; all three of those paths break under the App Sandbox unless
  we add temporary exception entitlements we do not want to maintain.
  The shell is local-first and ships with a strict CSP
  (`default-src 'self'`) plus a narrow IPC capability list, so the
  marginal isolation the sandbox adds is not worth the loss of
  legitimate filesystem access.
-->
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
    <!--
        Persist grants the user gives through the native folder/file
        picker (NSOpenPanel) so that we do not re-prompt on every
        `dialog.open()` call and we do not re-prompt on every fresh
        launch of the app once the user has approved a scan root.
    -->
    <key>com.apple.security.files.user-selected.read-write</key>
    <true/>

    <!--
        The webview itself is a JIT-less runtime, but Tauri 2's
        bundler links code that requires the standard hardened-runtime
        allowances below. Keeping these explicit makes the security
        posture self-documenting and matches the entitlements Tauri
        ships in its own macOS examples.
    -->
    <key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-unsigned-executable-memory</key>
    <true/>
    <key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-jit</key>
    <true/>
</dict>
</plist>
